06589nam a22009615i 9780824843212DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029824858  a(OCoLC)1032684287  a(OCoLC)1037982308  a(OCoLC)1041993790  a(OCoLC)1046607037  a(OCoLC)1047003824  a(OCoLC)1049629015  a(OCoLC)1054877689  a97808248432127 a10.1515/97808248432122doi  a(DE-B1597)483999  a(OCoLC)1013948813  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aGN666b.B65 2006 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.80099422200aBoundary Writing :bAn Exploration of Race, Culture, and Gender Binaries in Contemporary Australia /ced. by Lynette Russell. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b7 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. From Beats to Cybersex: Australian Gay Male Appropriation of Public Spaces -- tChapter 3. The Nonsurgical Option: Deciding Not to Decide about Gender Identity -- tChapter 4. Non-Anglo and Non-Aboriginal Australian: Multiculturalism, the Third Side of the Black/White Divide -- tChapter 5. Cultural Calculus: Cultural Translation and the Politics of Indigenous Cultural Property -- tChapter 6. “. . . different lives in different places”: A Space for Multiple White Identities through Aboriginal Rock Music -- tChapter 7. Indigenous Rights and the Mutability of Cultures: Tradition, Change, and the Politics of Recognition -- tChapter 8. Beyond Orality and Literacy: Textuality, Modernity, and Representation in Gularabulu: Stories from the West Kimberley -- tChapter 9. Rom and the Academy Repositioned: Binary Models in Yolŋu Intellectual Traditions and their Application to Wider Intercultural Dialogues -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHave globalization and the emergence of virtual cultures reduced cultural diversity? Will the world become homogenized or Americanized? Boundary Writing sets out to demonstrate that this oversimplification denies the reality that today there is greater space for cultural diversity than ever before. It explores the desire to categorize individuals and collectivities into racial, ethnic, gender, and sexuality categories (black and white, men and women, gay and straight), which is a feature of most Western societies. More specifically, it analyzes the boundaries and edges of these categories and concepts. Across nine chapters, contributors reveal that such binaries are often too restrictive. Through a series of case studies they consider how these various concepts overlap, coincide, and at times conflict.They investigate the tension between these classifications that in turn produce individual speaking positions. Many people—indigenous, native, Anglo-settler, recent migrants of diverse ethnic backgrounds, gay, transgender, queer—occupy an "in between" position that is strategically shifting with the social, political, and economic circumstances of the individual. In Boundary Writing, the reader will journey through various complex permutations of identity and in particular the ways in which indigeneity, race, sex, and gender interact and even counter-act one another.Contributors: Erez Cohen, Aaron Corn, Bruno David, Neparrna Gumbula, Michele Grossman, Myfanwy McDonald, Clive Moore, Stephen Pritchard, Liz Reed, Lynette Russell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCultural pluralismzAustralia. 0aEthnic groupszAustralia. 0aEthnologyzAustralia. 0aGroup identityzAustralia. 0aMinoritieszAustralia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Erez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu